entry.title: Reland "[TTFPassGen] Move PasswordGenerationAgent::FocusedElementChanged call earlier"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 3c1a89031d0a3c5ef1c89a89c637ca80b1bcc629



The original CL was reverted because of the failing PasswordManagerUIUtilAndroid::ShouldNotAcceptFocusEventAfterLoosingFocus test (it's renamed to ShouldNotAcceptFocusEventAfterFrameLostFocus currently) on the android-bf-cache bot. The test was re-writted and now passes.



Original change's description:

> [TTFPassGen] Move PasswordGenerationAgent::FocusedElementChanged call earlier

>

> Now PasswordGenerationAgent::FocusedNodeHasChanged is called from AutofillAgent::DidCompleteFocusChangeInFrame, which happens later then the virtual keyboard is shown (when a text input element is navigated).

> It feels more natural to move the FocusedNodeHasChanged call to AutofillAgent::HandleFocusChangeComplete, which happens before triggering the keyboard. This is needed for the password generation bottom sheet (the bottom sheet should be able to suppress the keyboard before it's triggered).

entry.title: [WebUI] Migrate GuestOSInstallerUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
This CL migrates GuestOSInstallerUI to WebUIConfig. It also removes the

GURL argument from the GuestOSInstallerUI constructor as it is unused.



Context:



Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.



Bug: 1317510

entry.title: Revert "[Office upload] Use BrowserListObserver to wait for created Files app"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 9089c92681121f77bda5c622d902dd94cc0aa80d.



Reason for revert: Suspected to introduce this build failure: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/test/chrome%3Aci/ninja%3A%2F%2Fchrome%2Ftest%3Abrowser_tests%2FDriveTest.OfficeFallbackTryAgain?q=VHASH%3A2535fc64adc4f4c8



Original change's description:

> [Office upload] Use BrowserListObserver to wait for created Files app

>

> When we didn't have a Files app window to use as a modal parent for

> our dialog, we created a new Files app window and used it as the

> parent. But this didn't work because the callback we provide to

> ShowItemInFolder gets called early in the launch process, before

> the actual Files app is launched.

>

> Instead use BrowserListObserver to catch when a new Browser is

> added, check that it's the Files app window we were expecting,

> and launch our dialog with this window as the modal parent.

>

> Several tests didn't use "real" files, they just created

> FileSystemURLs to plausible locations. This meant that

> ShowItemInFolder() failed to launch Files app in tests, which

> now causes CloudOpenTask to never make progress. Use the default

> browser() in several tests to avoid this problem.

>

> Update NewModalParentCreatedWithExisting to more directly

> capture and check the Browser that was created by CloudOpenTask.

entry.title: Migrate RemoteMaintenanceCurtainUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
Context:



Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.

entry.title: Dispatch shelf visibility changes after state change
entry.content:
Shelf (and shelf layout manager) have a WillChangeVisibilityState

observer interface - as the name suggests, observers were notified about

state change before the state actually changes. This changes the logic

to notify observers about shelf visibility state changes after the state

changes (so the visibility state passed to observers matches the current

shelf layout manager state). Most of the observers did not care about

whether the change happened before or after they are notified.

The order matters in Shelf::AutoDimEventHandler, and in this case it was

incorrect - Shelf::AutoDimEventHandler calls

ShelfLayoutManager::SetDimmed, which is no-op if the shelf is not in a

visible state (i.e. it depends on the *current* shelf visibility state).

entry.title: Various AddressMapOwnerLinux and NetworkChangeNotifierLinux changes
entry.content:
In the browser process, we need to access the

NetworkChangeNotifierLinux's AddressTrackerLinux in order to retrieve

its initial AddressMap (to send to the network service) and to tell it

to start recording changes it receives from the kernel.



In the network process, we need to access the

NetworkChangeNotifierPassive's AddressMapCacheLinux to set the initial

AddressMap (received from the browser process), and to apply any diffs

received from the browser process.



This CL is the necessary plumbing so that content/browser and

services/network can perform those operations.

entry.title: [BestEffortServiceWorker] Use OriginTrial token to enable the feature
entry.content:
This CL enables ServiceWorkerBypassFetchHandler with the

`all_with_race_network_request` option (aka BestEffortServiceWorker) via

OriginTrial token.



We add the new option named

`ServiceWorkerFetchHandlerBypassOption::kRaceNetworkRequest` to

ServiceWorkerFetchHandlerBypassOption mojom, so that we can pass the

info that the loader should trigger RaceNetworkRequest from browser

to renderer. Once ServiceWorkerMainResourceLoader confirmed there is a

valid OriginTrial token, set

`ServiceWorkerFetchHandlerBypassOption::kRaceNetworkRequest`. Then

ServiceWorkerSubresourceLoader which is on a renderer side lookup

fetch_handler_bypass_option and dispatch RaceNetworkRequest.

entry.title: [Office upload] Use BrowserListObserver to wait for created Files app
entry.content:
When we didn't have a Files app window to use as a modal parent for

our dialog, we created a new Files app window and used it as the

parent. But this didn't work because the callback we provide to

ShowItemInFolder gets called early in the launch process, before

the actual Files app is launched.



Instead use BrowserListObserver to catch when a new Browser is

added, check that it's the Files app window we were expecting,

and launch our dialog with this window as the modal parent.



Several tests didn't use "real" files, they just created

FileSystemURLs to plausible locations. This meant that

ShowItemInFolder() failed to launch Files app in tests, which

now causes CloudOpenTask to never make progress. Use the default

browser() in several tests to avoid this problem.



Update NewModalParentCreatedWithExisting to more directly

capture and check the Browser that was created by CloudOpenTask.



Bug: b:275950760

entry.title: Fix dangling pointer issues in MediaRouterUiForTestBase.
entry.content:
MediaRouterUiForTestBase currently holds a pointer to a

MediaRouterDialogControllerViews, which is a WebContentsUserData

subclass. However, several MediaRouterUiForTestBase implementations are

also WebContentsUserData subclasses.



This turns out to be problematic for dangling pointers, because the

order of destruction of different WebContentsUserDatas registered with

the same WebContents is *not* guaranteed.



It turns out that the various MediaRouterUiForTestBase subclasses don't

need to be WebContentsUserData and can simply be strongly owned by the

test fixture instead. This fixes the dangling pointer errors triggered

by the undefined order of destruction of WebContentsUserDatas, and, as a

bonus, fixes an untriaged dangling pointer error.
